            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pricing Power Superiority:</strong> If inflation continues to stay moderately high, Colgate's strong brand equity allows it to pass on costs better than generic rivals, potentially driving FCF growth higher than 5%.</li>
    <li><strong>Emerging Market Acceleration:</strong> A larger percentage of growth coming from less penetrated emerging markets (like India or LATAM) could steepen the revenue trajectory beyond our conservative terminal growth rate.</li>
    <li><strong>Margin Optimization:</strong> Future operational restructuring or supply chain automation could permanently raise FCF margins.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Commodity Costs & Forex:</strong> As a global seller, a strong dollar or sharp spikes in raw material costs can compress margins if price hikes fail to keep up without losing volume.</li>
    <li><strong>Private Label Substitution:</strong> In a tough economy, consumers trading down to store-brand oral care and pet nutrition products could erode Colgate's market share and volume growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Burden:</strong> The model accurately penalizes the company for its debt load, but rising interest rates on refinancing could squeeze net margins over time.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 7% discount rate for Colgate-Palmolive?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents the required rate of return. Because Colgate is a highly stable, non-cyclical consumer staples company with a low beta, it carries less market risk than the average stock. Therefore, investors accept a lower premium over the risk-free rate (10Y Treasury).</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the Net Cash negative?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Colgate-Palmolive carries significantly more debt than cash on its balance sheet. This is common for mature, highly cash-generative companies that use debt to optimize their capital structure and fund share buybacks or dividends. We subtract this net debt from the Enterprise Value to find the Equity Value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why assume only 5% FCF growth?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Colgate operates in mature categories (oral care, personal care, pet nutrition). Volume growth is typically low single digits globally. Additional growth comes from price mix. A 5% rate represents steady, resilient performance without relying on aggressive (and risky) M&A or unnatural market expansion.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in these assumptions. This tool is provided for educational purposes.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

